Introduction

A large cell-phone service provider, has requested our help to explore their customer data. They have requested two things:

  • Visual analysis of their customers, in-depth analysis of customers that end contracts.
  • An assessment of which of their new customers are likely to leave in the next quarter.

I will begin by importing the data into R for initial exploration and to conduct any necessary cleaning or mutating of raw data.

Data Wrangling

Load Packages

library(sqldf)
library(dplyr)

Import Data

Set working directory to folder location.

account_activity <- read.csv("account_activity.csv")  
customer_info <- read.csv("customer_info.csv")  
new_customers <- read.csv("new_customers.csv")

Data Exploration

In this section, I explored the three datasets and uncovered the following:

  • Both account_activity and customer_info include duplicated entries for 40 customer_ids.
  • Datasets are missing a Total_Calls aggregation of day, evening, night, and international calls.
  • There is a discrepancy in the account details information we are given about customers. There are three distinct area codes but the state column spans 51 states.
    • For this analysis, I will disregard the state column and assume this quarterly dataset is for customers in the Northern California / Bay Area region since the volumes align more with that scenario. Before using the state information I would need to research what that is referring to.

Data Cleaning and Mutating

In this section, I performed various transformations and cleanings. They include:

  • Removed duplicate entries in account_activity and customer_info datasets.
  • Created new Total_Calls column in both account_activity and new_customers.
  • Renamed Customer.ID to Customer_ID
  • Renamed total_Mins to Total_Mins
  • Joined account_activity and customer_info into customer_activity.

For the purposes of this analysis, I will assume there are no data integrity issues with the duplicated entries. In a real world scenario, I would want to investigate further to identify what caused the duplicates.

Remove duplicates

account_activity_unique <- unique(account_activity)
customer_info_unique <- unique(customer_info)

Add Total Calls column

account_activity_unique$Total_Calls <- account_activity_unique$Day_Calls + account_activity_unique$Eve_Calls + account_activity_unique$Night_Calls + account_activity_unique$Intl_Calls

new_customers$Total_Calls <- new_customers$Day_Calls + new_customers$Eve_Calls + new_customers$Night_Calls + new_customers$Intl_Calls

Rename Id columns

colnames(account_activity_unique)[1] <- 'Customer_ID' 
colnames(customer_info_unique)[1] <- 'Customer_ID'

Fix case mismatch

account_activity_unique <- rename(account_activity_unique, Total_Mins = total_Mins)
new_customers <- rename(new_customers, Total_Mins = total_Mins)

Join datasets for visualization and predictive analyses

customer_activity <- sqldf("SELECT A.*, B.State, B.Area_Code, B.Phone, B.Intl_Plan, B.VMail_Plan, B.Churn
                                FROM account_activity_unique A
                                LEFT JOIN customer_info_unique B
                                ON A.Customer_ID = B.Customer_ID")

Predictive Models

Split the customer activity data into training and test sets

library(caTools)

set.seed(3000)
spl = sample.split(customer_activity$Churn, SplitRatio = 0.7)
Train = subset(customer_activity, spl==TRUE)
Test = subset(customer_activity, spl==FALSE)

Logistic Regression

For simplicity of the model, I chose the high-level aggregations for my independent variables.

churnLog = glm(Churn ~ VMail_Message + Total_Mins + Total_Charge + Total_Calls
               + CustServ_Calls + Intl_Plan + VMail_Plan
               , data = Train, family=binomial)

Using the Log model to predict churn in new customers dataset.

Churn_predictLog = predict(churnLog, type="response", newdata=new_customers)
new_customer_predictions <- cbind(new_customers, Churn_predictLog)
new_customer_predictions$Churn_predictLog <-ifelse(new_customer_predictions$Churn_predictLog > .51, "1", "0")
new_customer_predictions$Churn_predictLog <- as.factor(new_customer_predictions$Churn_predictLog)

Classification and Regression Trees

This method builds what is called a tree by splitting on the values of the independent variables. Some advantages of CART are that it does not assume a linear model, like linear or log regression, and its a very interpretable model.

library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)

I use the same independent variables for this method.

ChurnTree = rpart(Churn ~ VMail_Message + Total_Mins + Total_Charge + Total_Calls
                   + CustServ_Calls + Intl_Plan + VMail_Plan
                   , data = Train, method="class", minbucket=25)

To predict the outcome for a new observation or case, you can follow the splits in the tree and at the end, you predict the most frequent outcome in the training set that followed the same path.

rpart.plot(ChurnTree
           , uniform=TRUE, compress=TRUE
           , fallen=T, branch=1, round=0, cex.main=1
           , split.round=0
           , branch.lwd=.5, split.lwd=.5, nn.lwd=.5
           , main = "Classification Tree for Customer Churn")

Make predictions

PredictCART = predict(ChurnTree, newdata = Test, type = "class")
table(Test$Churn, PredictCART)
##    PredictCART
##       0   1
##   0 855   0
##   1  54  91
(855+91)/(855+91+55+0)
## [1] 0.9450549

ROC curve; Tree Model Accuracy = 0.94

library(ROCR)

PredictROC = predict(ChurnTree, newdata = Test)
PredictROC

pred = prediction(PredictROC[,2], Test$Churn)
perf = performance(pred, "tpr", "fpr")
plot(perf)
title('ROC Curve for Customer Churn Tree')

Using the CART model to predict churn in new customers dataset.

Churn_predictTree = predict(ChurnTree, newdata = new_customer_predictions, type = "class")
new_customer_predictions <- cbind(new_customer_predictions, Churn_predictTree)

Conclusion

In this analysis, we used historical data to train a model that predicts customer churn. We used that model on new customer data to predict between 5-9% churn. In addition, we identified the following variables as drivers of customer churn:

Significant variables:

  • Customer Service Calls
  • Total Charge
  • Having an international plan
  • Having a voicemail plan
  • Voicemail messages

I propose the following next steps:

  • Intervention with the customers identified as likely to cancel their account.
  • Expand and investigate the customer service call and total charge feautures.
    • What are the root causes for high customer service calls?
    • Are customers satisfied with their customer service experience? Are their issues/questions being resolved?
    • Are the issues these customers facing preventable?
    • Collect data on phone service quality like dropped calls, etc.
    • Collect more granular data on service plan details, cost per minute, cost per month, fixed plan costs, promotions, etc.
  • Conduct cancellation surveys to identify new variables to begin collecting in customer activity or information datasets.
